         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> [12e]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> (One should tame) oneself, [13a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> with the self (that is well-tamed), [13c]  </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> [14a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> Therefore control (yourself!) [14c] </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> [1a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> [1c]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> [2a]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(The wise one) should drive away the ignorance. [2c] </seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> After having stroke down anger, [3b]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(of anger that is) rooted in poison, [3c] <hi>Sanskrit</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">(the good ones) praise (the killing of it), [3e] <hi>Sanskrit</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b6"><seg><seg type="prim_transl"><hi>Sanskrit</hi> the evil deed [4b]</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b7"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">one is tormented (afterwards) as if after having touched fire. [4d]</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels">Sanskrit (<bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>265-270</citedRange></bibl>)</note><note corresp="#a2" type="lingcomment">The TB compound <hi>ṣañ-añm</hi> is the usual translation of Skt. <hi>ātmānam</hi> (13a).</note><note corresp="#a5" type="lingcomment">We may assume that the Sanskrit imperative <hi>saṃ-yamaya</hi> (14c) has been translated by the imperative of the verb <hi>wlāw<hi rend="superscript">ā</hi>-</hi> ‘control’ which is always inflected in the middle; cf. also <hi>indrinta pulāwat</hi> “Control the senses!” in <ref type="ms" target="txt:m-pkas17h"/> b3.</note><note corresp="#b4" type="lingcomment">TB <hi>wse-witsakantso</hi> is a possessive compound corresponding to Skt. <hi>viṣa-mūla-</hi> ‘having poison as root’. It is in the plural because it is certainly the epithet of TB <hi>tremi</hi> ‘anger, wrath’ which is a plurale tantum. The genitive plural ending shows a mobile <hi>-o</hi> even though this is not a metrical text; however, immediately in front of interpunction, <hi>o-</hi>mobile is not unattested even in prose texts (see <bibl><title corresp="ref:malzahn2012a"/></bibl>).</note><note corresp="#b5" type="lingcomment">The verb TB <hi>pällānträ</hi> is the obvious restoration for the match of Skt. <hi>praśaṃsanti</hi> (3c).</note><note corresp="#b6" type="lingcomment">TB <hi>yolo yāmor</hi> ‘evil deed’ seems to be the most straightforward translation of Skt. <hi>duṣkṛtaṃ</hi> because this word has been taken as a substantive.</note><note corresp="#b7" type="lingcomment">The restoration of the present middle with passive value <hi>palkṣtär</hi> (and not the intransitive) of the verb <hi>pälk<hi rend="superscript">(ā)</hi>-</hi> ‘to burn, be tormented’ is warranted by the fact that it is a morphological calque of Skt. <hi>tapyate</hi>.</note></p>
         </div>
