               <item n="m_lingcomment_old">&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a2.&lt;/b&gt; The TB compound &lt;i&gt;ṣañ-añm&lt;/i&gt; is the usual translation of Skt. &lt;i&gt;ātmānam&lt;/i&gt; (13a). &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;a5.&lt;/b&gt; We may assume that the Sanskrit imperative &lt;i&gt;saṃ-yamaya&lt;/i&gt; (14c) has been translated by the imperative of the verb &lt;i&gt;wlāw&lt;sup&gt;ā&lt;/sup&gt;-&lt;/i&gt; ‘control’ which is always inflected in the middle; cf. also &lt;i&gt;indrinta pulāwat&lt;/i&gt; “Control the senses!” in [[PK AS 17H]] b3.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b4.&lt;/b&gt; TB &lt;i&gt;wse-witsakantso&lt;/i&gt; is a possessive compound corresponding to Skt. &lt;i&gt;viṣa-mūla-&lt;/i&gt; ‘having poison as root’. It is in the plural because it is certainly the epithet of TB &lt;i&gt;tremi&lt;/i&gt; ‘anger, wrath’ which is a plurale tantum. The genitive plural ending shows a mobile &lt;i&gt;-o&lt;/i&gt; even though this is not a metrical text; however, immediately in front of interpunction, &lt;i&gt;o-&lt;/i&gt;mobile is not unattested even in prose texts (see [[Malzahn 2012a]]).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b5.&lt;/b&gt; The verb TB &lt;i&gt;pällānträ&lt;/i&gt; is the obvious restoration for the match of Skt. &lt;i&gt;praśaṃsanti&lt;/i&gt; (3c).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b6.&lt;/b&gt; TB &lt;i&gt;yolo yāmor&lt;/i&gt; ‘evil deed’ seems to be the most straightforward translation of Skt. &lt;i&gt;duṣkṛtaṃ&lt;/i&gt; because this word has been taken as a substantive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;b&gt;b7.&lt;/b&gt; The restoration of the present middle with passive value &lt;i&gt;palkṣtär&lt;/i&gt; (and not the intransitive) of the verb &lt;i&gt;pälk&lt;sup&gt;(ā)&lt;/sup&gt;-&lt;/i&gt; ‘to burn, be tormented’ is warranted by the fact that it is a morphological calque of Skt. &lt;i&gt;tapyate&lt;/i&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;</item>
